A decorator in Python is a feature which adds functionality to an existing code.

A decorator is equal to assigning a function to a variable and call the variable to access the function

For example:-

def hello(func):
    print("Hello")
    return func   #NO ()

@hello
def greet(name):
    print(f" {name}")

These statements are equal to 
def greet(name):
    print(f" {name}")
greet = hello(greet)

This will print "Hello {name}" where name is the argument you pass.

